<subsection xml:id="subsec-sines-and-cosines-of-acute-angles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Sines and Cosines of Acute Angles</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_qdl2vmlk">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_z1xbsy6a">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_c03scjbr">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_1tbhe0vy">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_jwhyi0x3">
                        2.4 Trigonometry 1
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_sv11d5hs">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_hvj7ejsi">
                        Relate the sine, cosine and tangent of acute angles
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ipsmzm27" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_v6kuqrbt">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5a9owwpi" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_2ipv4931">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <introduction xml:id="auto_zfwn8roj" component="lesson-plan">
            <p xml:id="auto_5euh2fvw"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
            <ol>
                <li xml:id="auto_wzswhb8m">
                    <p xml:id="auto_654po3pc">
                        <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define sine and cosine as ratios in a right-angled triangle. State that sine uses the opposite side and hypotenuse, while cosine uses the adjacent side and hypotenuse. Explain that sine and cosine values depend only on the angle, not on the size of the triangle.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ac0m1ew7">
                    <p xml:id="auto_wvu30q3c">
                        <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Identify opposite, adjacent, and hypotenuse sides relative to a given angle. Calculate sine and cosine ratios from given measurements. Apply Pythagoras' theorem to find missing sides before computing trigonometric ratios.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_82b7ow83">
                    <p xml:id="auto_za3s6s6t">
                        <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Use sine and cosine to solve real-life problems involving right-angled triangles, such as finding the height reached by a ladder or the angle of elevation of the sun. Interpret and verify results in context.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_z89kvcp9">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/trigonometry-1/sines-and-cosines-of-acute-angles.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_aysq25cr">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/trigonometry-1/step-by-step-guide_sines-and-cosines-of-acute-angles.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery / Engage</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_gt0q1n10">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8salbt9u">
            <term>Teacher's Role During Discovery:</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ipu44z44">
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_tslact74">
                    <p xml:id="auto_2i2768x6">
                        Circulate among groups, ensuring students draw the diagram accurately with perpendicular lines.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6z3v8mg7">
                    <p xml:id="auto_l9kyx8nk">
                        <alert>Ask probing questions:</alert> <q>Are the three triangles similar?</q> <q>What do you notice about the first set of ratios?</q> <q>What about the second set of ratios?</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_icsygkpe">
                    <p xml:id="auto_nojg217t">
                        <alert>For struggling groups:</alert> <q>Focus on triangle OPA first. Measure AP (opposite) and OP (hypotenuse). Now calculate AP divided by OP. Do the same for triangle OQB.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qfsuxdbd">
                    <p xml:id="auto_2d6u0fxu">
                        <alert>For early finishers:</alert> <q>Can you predict what would happen if we drew more perpendicular lines at the same angle? Would the ratios stay the same?</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5b1tybtq">
                    <p xml:id="auto_fn9kzy8x">
                        Guide students to articulate: <q>The ratio of opposite to hypotenuse is constant. The ratio of adjacent to hypotenuse is also constant. These ratios depend only on the angle.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xiti7r6v">
                    <p xml:id="auto_zhugwdfg">
                        Identify 2–3 groups with clear results to share with the class.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pbkilj63">
                    <p xml:id="auto_9z143e6x">
                        If you have an Internet connection, show Learners the interactive exploration. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_m371pwam">
            <alert>Discovery Table: Linking Observations to Mathematical Significance</alert>
        </p>
        <tabular halign="left" bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                <cell>Student Observation</cell>
                <cell>Mathematical Significance</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>The ratios AP/OP, BQ/OQ, and CR/OR are all equal</cell>
                <cell>This constant ratio is the sine of the angle <m>\theta</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>The ratios OA/OP, OB/OQ, and OC/OR are all equal</cell>
                <cell>This constant ratio is the cosine of the angle <m>\theta</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>The first set uses opposite side and hypotenuse</cell>
                <cell><m>\sin \theta = \frac{\text{Opposite}}{\text{Hypotenuse}}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>The second set uses adjacent side and hypotenuse</cell>
                <cell><m>\cos \theta = \frac{\text{Adjacent}}{\text{Hypotenuse}}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Both ratios are constant for a given angle</cell>
                <cell>Sine and cosine depend only on the angle, not the triangle size</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_ck7pa5a2">
