        </p>
    </activity>
    <exploration xml:id="auto_16yn1m64">
        <title>Exploring Sine and Cosine Ratios</title>
        <figure xml:id="fig-sine-cosine-interactive">
            <caption>Interactive Activity: Discovering Sine and Cosine Ratios</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="interactive-sine-cosine" platform="jsxgraph" width="95%" aspect="4:3" source="jsxgraph/sines-and-cosines-of-acute-angles.js">
                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-sine-cosine" surface="jsxboard" aspect="4:3"/>
                <instructions xml:id="inst-sine-cosine">
                    <p xml:id="auto_4kocm2h6">
                        Use this interactive board to explore the relationship between the angle and the sides of the right-angled triangles:
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_dabiganf">
                        <ul>
                            <li xml:id="auto_a6sluchm">
                                <alert>Adjust the Angle:</alert> Drag the <m>\theta</m> slider. As the angle changes, what happens to the lengths of the opposite sides and the hypotenuses of the three triangles?
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_mgmxb4zy">
                                <alert>Change Triangle Sizes:</alert> Slide points <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> horizontally. How does resizing the base (adjacent side) of the triangle affect the lengths of the other two sides?
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_ghbumsg0">
                                <alert>Explore the Sine Ratios:</alert> Look at the left column of calculations below the graph. Try moving points <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> while keeping the angle constant. What do you notice about the ratio of the <term>Opposite</term> side divided by the <term>Hypotenuse</term>? How does this value compare to the sine of <m>\theta</m> calculated at the top?
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_dhuoa6j3">
                                <alert>Explore the Cosine Ratios:</alert> Now look at the right column. When you change the angle <m>\theta</m>, how does the ratio of the <term>Adjacent</term> side divided by the <term>Hypotenuse</term> change? Does dragging points <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, or <m>C</m> to change the size of the triangles alter this ratio?
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
    </exploration>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction / Explain</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_3m46gldr">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0mp7kanv">
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_19ezx6f6">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_plo6gyfz">
                    <p xml:id="auto_nww52u7z">
                        <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>Sine and cosine are the same thing.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> <q>No, sine uses opposite and hypotenuse, while cosine uses adjacent and hypotenuse.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_r8t8keor">
                    <p xml:id="auto_2o0vwr7k">
                        <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I can use any two sides for sine or cosine.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> <q>No, sine always uses opposite and hypotenuse. Cosine always uses adjacent and hypotenuse.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_szcb17g3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ji457vso">
                        <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>The values change if I make the triangle bigger.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> <q>No, sine and cosine depend only on the angle. Similar triangles have the same sine and cosine values.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_f90ufntp">
                    <p xml:id="auto_mt5foh60">
                        <alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>Sine and cosine can be greater than 1.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> <q>No, since the hypotenuse is always the longest side, sine and cosine values range from 0 to 1.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <insight xml:id="auto_p7tkrw0g">
        <p xml:id="auto_dqiu1u0r">
            You will notice that,
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_095i970v">
            <ol xml:id="auto_88l475rs" marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_xhrwkgsc">
                    <p xml:id="auto_dgsk7z81">
                        The ratios of (3) are the same and is expressed as;
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_18l1uize">
                        <m>\frac{AP}{OP}=\frac{BQ}{OQ}=\frac{CR}{OR}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_3u9wtv6i">
                        This constant value is obtained by taking
                        the ratio of the side <term>opposite</term> to the angle
                        <m>\theta </m> to the <term>hypotenuse</term> side in each case.
                        This ratio is called the sine of angle <m>\theta </m>, which can be written as as <m>\sin \, \theta</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                    <li xml:id="auto_ip61z2df">
                    <p xml:id="auto_lzpsihp8">
                        The ratios of (5) are the same and is expressed as;
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_4elr89il">
                        <m>\frac{OA}{OP}=\frac{OB}{OQ}=\frac{OC}{OR}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_tg5mmqd1">
                        This constant value is obtained by taking
                        the ratio of the side <term>adjacent</term> to the angle
                        <m>\theta </m> to the <term>hypotenuse</term> side in each case.
                        This ratio is called the cosine of angle <m>\theta </m>, which can be written as <m>\cos \, \theta</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_sbhddjwd">
            In general, given a right-angled triangle whith <m>\textbf{opposite side, adjacent side}</m> and <m>\textbf{hypotenuse side}</m> as shown,
        </p>
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="Triangle12">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Points
                        \coordinate (A) at (5,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (5,3);

                        % Triangle
                        \draw[thick] (B) -- node[below]{Adjacent} (A) -- node[right]{Opposite} (C) -- node[sloped,above]{Hypotenuse} (B);

                        % Right angle box at A
                        \draw (A) -- ++(-0.3,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0);

                        % Angle theta at B
                        \draw [blue,very thick](1,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=30,radius=1cm];
                        \node [right]at (0.9,0.3) {\(\theta\)};

                        % Labels
                        \node[ left] at (B) {B};
                        \node[right] at (A) {A};
                        \node[ right] at (C) {C};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
            
        </image>
        <p xml:id="auto_8kqqpesq">
            <md>
                <mrow> \tan \, \theta=\amp \frac{\text{Opposite}}{\text{Adjacent}} </mrow>
                <mrow> \cos\, \theta =\amp \frac{\text{Adjacent}}{\text{Hypotenuse}}</mrow>
                <mrow> \sin\,\theta =\amp \frac{\text{Opposite}}{\text{Hypotenuse}}</mrow>
                
            </md>
        </p>
    </insight>
    <note xml:id="auto_7kwax32s">
        <p xml:id="auto_o4gqdepi">
            The above formula also applies to the trigonometric ratios for  <m>\alpha</m>.
        </p>
    </note>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_xo0s6ylr">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_e2tasyvl">
            Learners work through the worked examples and guided practice problems. Encourage learners to identify opposite, adjacent, and hypotenuse sides before setting up any ratio.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_xe9cjhwt">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_2b1id1i7">
                In the figure below, <m>MN=5\, cm\,,NO=12\,cm \,\text{and} \, \angle MNO=90^\circ</m>. Calculate:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_rnyj0wc8">
                <ol xml:id="auto_eal67vq9" marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_xs9hncxh">
                        <p xml:id="auto_f8ntx6q1">
                            <m>\sin\,\theta</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ite158sf">
                        <p xml:id="auto_z8bsu2iq">
                            <m>\cos\,\theta</m>
                        </p>

                    </li>

                </ol>
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="Triangle13">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Coordinates (scaled to 5:12 triangle)
                    \coordinate (N) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (O) at (4,0);
                    \coordinate (M) at (0,1.67);

                    % Triangle
                    \draw[thick] (N) -- (M) -- (O) -- cycle;

                    % Right angle at N
                    \draw (N) -- ++(0.3,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(-0.3,0);

                    % Labels
                    \node at (M) [above left] {M};
                    \node at (N) [below left] {N};
                    \node at (O) [below right] {O};

                    \node at (-0.4,0.85) {5 cm};
                    \node at (2,-0.4) {12 cm};

                    % Proper inward arc for theta at O
                    \draw (O) ++(160:0.5) arc[start angle=160, end angle=200, radius=0.3];
                    \node[left] at (3.4,0.2) {$\theta$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_06br8oyf">
                <ol xml:id="auto_5o4g3lw2" marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_1pugt9qq">
                        <p xml:id="auto_xw0dlrxj">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> sin\,\theta=\amp \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{hypotenuse}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{MN}{MO}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{5}{MO} </mrow>
                                
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_sd1i306r">
                            Recall: <md>
                                <mrow> MO^2=\amp 12^2+5^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 144+ 25</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 169</mrow>
                                <mrow>MO= \amp 13\,cm </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_1pgz6spw">
                            Thus, <md>
                                <mrow>sin \,\theta= \amp \frac{5}{13}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp  0.3846</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_d7spmzvt">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qlc9dvqs">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> cos\,\theta=\amp \frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{hypotenuse}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{NO}{MO} </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{12}{13} </mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 0.9231 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
